data.content:
Here's the complete migration analysis and replacement code.

## Issue Inventory

| Line | API | Problem on .NET 8 |
|------|-----|--------------------|
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | `Thread.Interrupt` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); not a reliable wake mechanism |
| `_thread.Abort()` | `Thread.Abort` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | Can't be interrupted by cancellation without `WaitHandle.WaitAny` |
| `while (true)` | Loop condition | No cooperative exit — requires abort to stop |

**Bonus bug in the original:** `ManualResetEvent.Set()` followed by `Reset()` can lose signals when multiple items are enqueued rapidly — only one dequeue per wake cycle.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

The cleanest replacement uses `Channel<T>`, which replaces the `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` triple and natively supports `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — don't propagate
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();                    // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline
        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread` + `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | `Channel<string>` | Thread-safe producer/consumer with built-in backpressure and cancellation |
| `while (true)` with no exit | `await foreach` with `CancellationToken` | Cooperative cancellation — exits cleanly |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_channel.Writer.Complete()` | Signals the reader to drain and stop |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` | Hard deadline if drain takes too long |
| `new Thread(RunLoop)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Task-based model; no raw thread management |
| Lost-signal bug | `Channel` handles all queueing | Every enqueued item is guaranteed to be read |

## If you must keep it synchronous

Use `BlockingCollection<T>` — it's the synchronous equivalent:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();       // graceful: drain remaining items
        if (!_thread?.Join(5000) ?? false)
            _cts.Cancel();             // hard stop after 5s
        _thread?.Join(1000);           // wait for cancellation to take effect
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
        _queue.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`CancellationToken` doesn't interrupt `Handle(item)`** — if `Handle` does long-running work, pass the token into it and check `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at safe points
2. **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timers and callbacks if not disposed
3. **Don't catch and swallow `OperationCanceledException` deep in the call chain** — only catch it at the top-level loop as shown
4. **`Channel.Writer.Complete()` vs `_cts.Cancel()`** — use `Complete()` for graceful drain, `Cancel()` for hard stop. The pattern above does both with a timeout
